  "text": "Django's admin filter rendering pipeline for ForeignKey filters follows this control flow:\n\n1. **Filter Definition (django/contrib/admin/filters.py)**:\n   - `ListFilter` (line 26) is the abstract base class that defines the `has_output()` method (line 41-47), which must be implemented by all filter subclasses. This method determines whether a filter should be displayed in the sidebar.\n   - `RelatedFieldListFilter` (line 222) is the class responsible for rendering ForeignKey filter dropdowns. It inherits from `FieldListFilter` and overrides `has_output()` (line 248-253) to return `True` if there are lookup choices plus an optional empty choice.\n\n2. **Filter Collection (django/contrib/admin/views/main.py)**:\n   - The `ChangeList` class (line 67) manages the change list view. Its `get_filters()` method (line 175) is responsible for:\n     - Instantiating filter classes for each field in `list_filter`\n     - Calling `has_output()` on each filter (line 221)\n     - Only appending filters with truthy `has_output()` values to the `filter_specs` list (line 222)\n     - Returning `filter_specs` which is stored as `cl.filter_specs`\n\n3. **Template Tag Rendering (django/contrib/admin/templatetags/admin_list.py)**:\n   - The `admin_list_filter` template tag (line 521) is a simple_tag that renders individual filter instances by loading their template and calling `spec.choices(cl)` (line 526).\n\n4. **Template Iteration (django/contrib/admin/templates/admin/change_list.html)**:\n   - The change_list.html template iterates over all filters at line 72: `{% for spec in cl.filter_specs %}{% admin_list_filter cl spec %}{% endfor %}`\n   - Only filters that passed `has_output()` check are in `filter_specs`, so only those with output are rendered in the sidebar.\n\nThe key control point for determining filter visibility is the `has_output()` method, which is called during the `ChangeList.get_filters()` phase. For `RelatedFieldListFilter`, an empty filter (with no lookup choices) will not be displayed because `has_output()` returns `False` when there are zero choices.\n"
}

